{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":292740,"duration_api_ms":294988,"num_turns":17,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"7e25068d-9f47-48bb-9ca9-6c55a9411006","total_cost_usd":0.9540408999999999,"usage":{"input_tokens":13,"cache_creation_input_tokens":59158,"cache_read_input_tokens":461381,"output_tokens":9548,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":59158,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":13,"outputTokens":9548,"cacheReadInputTokens":461381,"cacheCreationInputTokens":59158,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.8391929999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":115,"outputTokens":7717,"cacheReadInputTokens":321754,"cacheCreationInputTokens":35178,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.11484789999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed all changes across src/adapters/fs.rs and src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs. The implementation correctly addresses all three issues from the project prompt:\n\n**Issue 1 (Journal struct drift):** Round-trip tests render via model.rs, parse via fs.rs, check every field, and compare re-rendered output to the original. Because serde silently drops unknown fields during deserialization, any field added to the model payload but missing from the fs struct causes the `assert_eq!(parsed.render(), rendered)` comparison to fail. Additionally, any new parameter added to `render_start_journal_details` or `render_completion_journal_details` would break the test at compile time since the function signatures change. Both StartJournalDetails and CompletionJournalDetails pairs are currently in sync (3 and 6 fields respectively).\n\n**Issue 2 (Runless-to-named completion):** New match arm in `update_task_run` at line 3042-3051 accepts a runless entry when `started_at` matches, then backfills run_id at line 3226-3227. Plan_hash conflict detection at lines 3229-3241 still rejects incompatible plan_hash values. The started_at guard prevents backfilling the wrong legacy attempt. Error messages now include both timestamps for diagnosability. The single-element slice pattern `[index]` ensures ambiguous multiple-open-match cases still error out.\n\n**Issue 3 (plan_hash auto-population):** Three locations correctly auto-populate: (a) new entry creation in `record_task_run` (line 2948-2950), (b) existing entry backfill in `record_task_run` (line 2916-2921), (c) non-terminal completion in `update_task_run` (line 3246-3249). All use `snapshot_plan_hash` which reads `status.json` and extracts the plan_hash. Caller-supplied plan_hash always takes precedence via the `or_else`/conditional checks. The auto-populate is correctly guarded by `entry.plan_hash.is_none()` so already-populated rows (e.g., from an earlier snapshot version) are never overwritten by a newer snapshot's plan_hash.\n\n**Edge cases verified:** (1) Start replay after plan evolution: entry retains hash_v1 even after snapshot advances to v2, because `plan_hash.is_none()` is false. (2) Terminal replay after plan evolution: `option_conflicts(Some(hash_v1), None)` returns false, so replay is accepted and hash_v1 is preserved. (3) Conflicting plan_hash on runless match: properly rejected even though started_at matches. (4) run_id backfill on failed plan_hash conflict: not persisted to disk since error returns before `write_task_runs`.\n\n**Concurrency:** Advisory file lock on task-runs.ndjson protects against concurrent writes. The snapshot read inside the lock may observe a concurrently-updated plan_hash, but this is a benign race since plan_hash auto-population is best-effort enrichment.\n\nAll 683 tests pass. No bugs, safety issues, or correctness gaps found.","amendments":[]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"2a5e9257-9e47-40f2-92d8-8dd80c3a813e"}
